{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"94d206ca-336b-40b9-9b43-535c5f5651a1","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. From inside the container:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` SDK isn't in the container, copy the tool binary in or use `kubectl cp` to extract the trace afterward.\n- For lower overhead or flame graphs, use **`dotnet-trace`** with `--format speedscope`.\n- If you need OS-level context (native frames, kernel), use **`perf`** or **`dotnet-counters`** first to confirm managed CPU is the bottleneck, then trace.\n\n```bash\n# Copy trace out of the pod\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7633d09a-ddb5-44bb-80fa-00d5e1bb8977","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":351,"requestId":"1BC2:13A3E2:C4FFF4:E22A34:6A028224"},"id":"8bc66937-ee9e-4f35-8742-f84fb9c30356","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:28:14.426Z","parentId":"d3019792-1b18-458d-b071-57b33a7ccca8"}
